 thought in Vedic sacrifice. Treating Vedic mantra as a sophisticated form of artistic composition, she develops the idea of metonymy, or associational thought, as a major motivator for the use of mantra in sacrificial performance. Filling a long-standing gap in our understanding, her book provides a history of the Indian interpretive imagination and a study of the mental creativity and hermeneutic sophistication of Vedic religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHinduismxRituals. 0aMantras. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh  aatharva veda.  abandhu.  abrahmana.  abrahmin.  aceremony.  achanting.  adeity.  adevata.  aeastern religion.  afood studies.  agrhya.  ahinduism.  ahymns.  aindia.  aindian sacrifice.  aindic religion.  amagic.  amantra.  ameditation.  ametonymy.  amindfulness.  aperformance theory.  aperformed poetry.  areligion.  areligious belief.  areligious history.  areligious poetry.  areligious practice.  arite.  aritual.  asacrifice.  asoma.  asouth asia.  aspirituality.  asrauta literature.  asupernatural.  atradition.  aupanisads.  avedic ritual.  avedic.  avidhana.  aviniyoga.  avisualization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024087240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093088940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930889423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930889/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY